\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Geographical confirmation of the reverse malaria hypothesis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Andre Python, Gavin Band
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Abstract.
 Selection due to 
\emph on
Plasmodium falciparum
\emph default
 malaria has driven human malaria-protective mutations, including the sickle
 haemoglobin allele (HbS), to high frequencies in sub-Saharan African population
s.
 Recent work has suggested that a competing selective effect may be occurring
 in parasite populations, with the identification of mutations in four loci
 termed 
\emph on
Pfsa
\emph default
 1-4 in the parasite genome that are strongly associated with HbS in both
 severe and mild infections in Africa 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Band2022,Hamilton2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A natural evolutionary hypothesis is that these mutations are positively
 selected for by the presence of HbS-carrying individuals.
 Here, we examine this by developing a n updated global map of HbS allele
 frequencies from available survey data, and using it to assess the geographic
 association between HbS and the 
\emph on
Pfsa+
\emph default
 mutations using Bayesian geostatistical regression models.
 We show that the 
\emph on
Pfsa+
\emph default
 mutations are strongly positively correlated with HbS frequencies across
 multiple scales, including within individual countries and across the continent
 of Africa.
 A possible exception to this rule is the Democratic Republic of Congo where
 the 
\emph on
Plasmodium falciparum
\emph default
 allele frequencies are among the highest observed globally.
 To interpret this, we propose a model in which the geographic variability
 in HbS frequency, coupled with a currently unknown counteracting selection
 force, leads to balanced polymorphism with geographically varying frequencies
 following a sigmoid relationship similar to observed data.
 The nature of the proposed counteracting force is currently unclear, but
 could be related to the observed long-range linkage desequilibrium displayed
 by the loci, a setting which would lead to complex evolutionary dynamics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset toc
LatexCommand tableofcontents

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Malaria caused by the parasite 
\emph on
Plasmodium falciparum
\emph default
 is a major cause of disease and death in tropical regions, with the highest
 burden falling upon young children in Africa.
 Because of this high childhood mortality, human genetic mutations which
 prevent the severe symptoms of malaria have been driven to high frequency
 in malaria-endemic populations through natural selection.
 This concept, originally termed the `malaria hypothesis', most famously
 applies to the sickle haemoglobin polymorphism (HbS), a mutation of the
 haemoglobin beta subunit which confers strong protection against severe
 malaria and reaches frequencies as high as XX% in some sub-Saharan African
 populations—but plausibly applies to other protective mutations as well
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Band2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, if a protective mutation affects parasite fitness—that is, if it
 reduces the level of infection, replication, and onwards transmission parasites
 are able to achieve—then it must also place selective pressure on parasite
 populations to coevolve.
 In recent work, the [Xth author] and colleagues provided evidence that
 this coevolution is taking place with respect to sickle haemoglobin 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Band2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 That work identified mutations in three regions of the parasite genome
 that are strongly associated to HbS, using a sample of severe infections
 from The Gambia and Kenya.
 The effect has also been replicated using community-sampled infections
 from Mali 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Band2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Ghana 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hamilton2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Moreover, a fourth locus associated with HbS and prevalent in west African
 populations was identified in the latter paper 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hamilton2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Collectively we refer to the loci as 
\shape italic
P.falciparum
\shape default
 sickle-associated (
\shape italic
Pfsa
\shape default
) loci 1-4 (detailed in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:pfsa-variants"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A key population-genetic hypothesis arising from this work is that the 
\shape italic
Pfsa
\shape default
 mutations are positively selected for in individuals who carry HbS.
 Some support for this hypothesis has been provided by an initial comparison
 of HbS and 
\shape italic
Pfsa
\shape default
 population allele frequencies indicating that they are positively correlated
 within Africa 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Band2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This analysis, however, was conducted at the relatively coarse level of
 countries, and did not attempt to quantify the relationship.
 Major questions remain outstanding including the extent and strength of
 selection, and the scale on which it occurs; for example, does HbS variation
 explain the strong 
\shape italic
Pfsa
\shape default
 population differentiation that has been observed in individual countries
 including Tanzania 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Moser2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and the Democratic republic of Congo (DRC) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Verity2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

? Perhaps the most intriguing puzzle, given that 
\shape italic
Pfsa+
\shape default
 parasites are clearly also able to infect and cause disease in non-carrier
 individuals (HbAA), is why the mutations remain at intermediate frequencies
 in African parasite populations.
 This might indicate a currently unknown fitness cost, possibly related
 to the unusual linkage disequilibrium (i.e.
 correlation) that is observed between the loci.
 Ultimately, functional studies will be needed to fully understand the underlyin
g biological mechanisms, but some progress can be made by a more detailed
 analysis of available population-genetic data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we address this by using available data to quantify the relationship
 between HbS and 
\shape italic
Pfsa
\shape default
 allele frequencies in global populations.
 Our analysis is based on a Bayesian geostatistical regression model that
 relates 
\shape italic
Pfsa+
\shape default
 and HbS frequencies, and takes into account available HbS survey data,
 and parasite population genetic data, from multiple sources.
 The method builds on an updated map of HbS frequency which extends previous
 work 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Piel2010,Piel2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, allowing us to fully account for uncertainty in the underlying frequencies.
 We use this with data on parasite allele frequencies from the MalariaGEN
 Pf7 datasets 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hamid2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, as well as two datasets based on molecular inversion probe genotyping
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Verity2020,Moser2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Applying this within Africa, we find that a positive correlation exists
 at both continental and finer scales, including separately in east and
 west Africa, and within individual countries where there is sufficient
 data to estimate the relationship.
 A possible exception, however, is DRC which is notable because this is
 where 
\shape italic
Pfsa+
\shape default
 frequencies appear highest.
 To explain these results, we investigate a simple model of parasite evolution
 in the presence of presumed positive selection due to HbS.
 We find that the combination of geographically varying HbS prevalence,
 together with a mild opposing selective force on Pfsa+ parasites, leads
 to a balancing selection scenario with stable equilibrium frequencies following
 an 'S-shaped' curve similar to the observed data.
 [possilbe sentence about epistasis / 4 loci].
 
\end_layout

