\begin_layout Subsection
Definition of the HbS and 
\shape italic
Pfsa
\shape default
 mutations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define HbS as the mutation chr11:XXX: 
\begin_inset Formula $T>A$
\end_inset

 in GRCh38 reference coordinates.
 HbS determines an amino acid change to the haemoglobin beta subunit HBB,
 that causes polymerisation of HBB leading to sickle-cell anaemia in individuals
 carrying two copies of the mutation (HbSS).
 Individuals with only one copy, i.e.
 heterozygous carries termed HbAS, typically do not suffer from anaemia.
 HbAS and HbAS can be measured either by assaying DNA for HbS mutation or
 by blood typing for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{S}$
\end_inset

 haemoglobin.
 In this work we combine survey data, collected from the literature and
 detailed below, which used several methods to determine HbS status.
 Full data collation methods are described in 
\series bold
Methods
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The details of sickle-associated mutations in the 
\shape italic
P.falciparum
\shape default
 malaria parasite genome are given in Table
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:pfsa-variants"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 For the purposes of this work, we estimate allele frequencies using available
 genotyping data from population samples.
 A complication is that a single individual may be infected with parasites
 with multiple genotypes (termed a mixed infection).
 In practice, available datasets typically call genotypes from sequence
 read data as if for a diploid sample, such that mixed genotypes indicate
 a substantial number of sequence reads supporting both alleles.
 For the purposes of this work we exclude such mixed calls from the allele
 frequency calculation.
 A full description of processing of parasite genetic data can be found
 in 
\series bold
Methods
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

