\begin_layout Standard
A detailed global map of HbS allele frequencies has published in 2010 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Piel2010"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and updated in 2013 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Piel2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This map was constructed using a Bayesian geospatial model which extends
 the frequencies observed at survey sampling points across the globe, by
 modelling the spatial autocorrelation in frequencies.
 However, only summary data from this map is currently available, and for
 our analysis we aimed to fully capture the uncertainty in the HbS survey
 data.
 We therefore chose to rebuild the map, focussing on Africa, using a common
 form of geostatistical model implemented using the R-INLA package 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Rue2009,Lindgren2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The likelihood function in this model (i.e.
 the modelled probability of survey point data) is expressed as a binomial
 logistic regression model including a baseline term (reflecting the log-odds
 of the global mean frequency, which is close to zero in practice) plus
 a location-specific deviation which is assumed to vary smoothly across
 geographical space.
 Specifically, we assume that the local deviations follow a joint Gaussian
 distribution with covariance at nearby points that reduces with distance;
 the exact form is governed by a Matérn covariance function whose parameters
 are estimated by model fitting.
 The modelled frequency at any given geographical point is then determined
 by this covariance function and any nearby survey points.
 A full specification of the model and priors is given in Methods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For our main analysis, we specified a range of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}=5$
\end_inset

 (indicating covariance extending over approximately 5 degrees latitude/longitud
e, i.e.
 approximately XXkm), and prior standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{0}=0.7$
\end_inset

 on the log-odds scale.
 This leads to a modest level of smoothing and produces a map similar to,
 but with slightly [less/more] smoothing than the previously published map
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Piel2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

(Supplementary Figure 2).
 As expected, we also observed improved model certainty near the locations
 of new survey points where the uncertainty in our map is substantially
 reduced, including in northwestern Tanzania and parts of Nigeria (
\series bold
Figure 1
\series default
).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The 
\emph on
Pfsa+
\emph default
 mutations are geographically correlated to HbS at multiple scales
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To assess the relationship between HbS and the 
\emph on
Pfsa+
\emph default
 alleles, we examined parasite population genetic data from Malaria Pf7
 resource[MalariaGEN Wellcome Open 2023] (which includes 20,864 samples
 from 33 countries, including over 11,000 from African populations) as well
 two studies which conducted geographic sampling from the Democratic Republic
 of Congo [Verity et al 2021] and from Tanzania [Moser et al 2021].
 The combined sample contains informative data from 268 locations in Africa,
 although geographical representation is still limited in some areas (
\series bold
Figure 1a)
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We used this data to develop a Bayesian regression method (see 
\series bold
Materials and Methods
\series default
) to estimate the local effect of the HbS allele frequency (
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}_{\text{HbS}}$
\end_inset

) on 
\emph on
Pfsa+
\emph default
 prevalence.
 This model compares the observed counts of 
\emph on
Pfsa+
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
Pfsa-
\emph default
 alleles, to the map-inferred frequency of HbS carries at each sampling
 location, and uses this to fit a regression line.
 The model has two specific innovations that make it robust to input datasets.
 First, it takes into account uncertainty in the HbS frequency by integrating
 over the full posterior distribution of the HbS global map (by using a
 sample of posterior estimates in practice).
 Second, to handle the geographic distributution of data points, which were
 sometimes sampled in close geographic proximity, we also model spatial
 autocorrelation between 
\emph on
Pfsa+
\emph default
 frequencies by incorporating a spatial component into the regression.
 In effect, similar to the HbS frequency map, this assumes that 
\emph on
Pfsa+
\emph default
 vary smoothly with geography.
 Given these components, the framework models the observed counts using
 a binomial distribution.
 A natural fit is to use a logistic link function (which dictates an 'S'-shaped
 relationship between HbAS/SS and Pfsa+ frequencies), but the framework
 also allows us to explore alternative links.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fitting this model to the complete data across Africa at the four Pf loci
 yields the estimates shown in Figure 1d-g (dashed lines).
 As previously observed
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Band2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Pfsa1+ and Pfsa3+ frequencies each have a positive relationship with HbAS/SS
 frequencies across the continent of Africa.
 The strength of this relationship is estimated by the underlying regression
 parameter; for a logistic regression model it is approximately ?? XX ??
 (AA - BB) indicating roughly a X% change in Pf+ frequency for a 1% change
 in HbAS/SS frequency.
 The Pfsa2 and Pfsa4 variants have similar behaviour, but they appear only
 at high frequencies in east (Pfsa2, Fig 1e) or west (Pfsa4, Fig 1f) Africa
 respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
