\begin_layout Subsection
Little evidence of recent increases in 
\emph on
Pfsa+
\emph default
 allele frequency
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The analyses above suggest consistent HbS-driven positive selection for
 Pfsa+ alleles across scales, and a natural question is whether they may
 be undergoing a selective sweep at present.
 An alternative possibility, given that the alleles do not appear to have
 fixed in any region of Africa, is that they are undergoing a form of balancing
 selection.
 To address these questions, we first examined patterns of Pfsa+-carrying
 haplotypes at the Pfsa1-4 loci using the Pf7 resource (Fig X).
 A the Pfsa3 locus, we excluded regions known to carry structural duplications
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Band2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 from this analysis.
 At all four loci, clustering of haplotypes indicates that the 
\emph on
Pfsa+
\emph default
 mutations lie on a haplotype background which is shared across all African
 populations (i.e.
 haplotypes cluster by Pfsa+ allele, rather than geography).
 This, together with the sharing of Pfsa3 structural variant types from
 multiple populations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Band2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 strongly suggests that each allele has a single mutational origin.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We used the iHS (and SDS?) metrics to examine evidence for recent positive
 selection at these alleles seperately within data from each country.
 Results of this analysis are presented in Supp Table X.
 With the exception of Democratic Republic of Congo, evidence was at best
 limited (P > 0.1).
 In samples from the Democratic Republic of Congo, modest evidence of recent
 increase was observed (P=XX).
 We note that these tests have limited power to detect partial selective
 sweeps when the alleles are les common,.
 Nevertheless, these results appear to rule out recent rapid upward mxovements
 in allele frequency in most populations studied.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Opposing fitnesses create stable equilibrium frequencies in a spatially
 varying population
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The presence of HbAS/SS individuals appears to create positive selection
 for 
\emph on
Pfsa+
\emph default
, and 
\emph on
Pfsa+
\emph default
 parasites can infect HbAA individuals (and cause severe disease) apparently
 successfully
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Band2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Moreover, HbS has been prevalent in modern populations for many centuries.
 Why then are the 
\emph on
Pfsa+
\emph default
 alleles still at intermediate frequencies in all populations where HbS
 is prevalent? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we show that the geographical variation shown above (Fig
 1) may in fact be enough to produce this behaviour.
 Specifically, we will develop a simple model of parasite evolution in a
 host population containing A and S alleles, which generates stable equilibrium
 frequencies when the frequency of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 alleles varies geographically.
 The key ingredient is to assume that both Pfsa- and Pfsa+ alleles incur
 a fitness cost, with Pfsa+ alleles assumed to be 'fit' when infecting S
 individuals, and Pfsa- alleles assumed to be 'fit' when infecting A individuals.
 Although this is somewhat akin to a 'matching alleles' model, current data
 suggest that Pfsa+ parasites are able to infect (and cause disease in)
 
\emph on
both
\emph default
 AA and AS/SS individuals in substantial numbers.
 A reasonable assumption may therefore be that the fitness cost on Pfsa+
 alleles in A carries is at most modest.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following this, we encode parasite fitness (i.e.
 chance of a successful infection when a host is bitten with an infected
 mosquito) by a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma=(\gamma_{xy})$
\end_inset

 for parasite alleles 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and host alleles 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Gamma=\left(\begin{array}{c|cc}
 & A & S\\
\hline - & \gamma_{-A} & \gamma_{-S}\\
+ & \gamma_{+A} & \gamma_{+S}
\end{array}\right)\quad\text{e.g.}\quad\Gamma=\gamma\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c|cc}
 & A & S\\
\hline - & 1 & 0.1\\
+ & 0.9 & 1
\end{array}\right)\label{eq:evolution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Entry 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{xy}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 encodes the fitness when a parasite with allele 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 sucessfully infects an individual with genotype 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 For concreteness, 'successful' here means that the infection grows sufficiently
 that it generates gametocytes, and can be transmitted to a subsequent mosquito.
 The values on the right represent a plausible situation similar to that
 outlined above, i.e.
 they encode a severe relative fitness cost for 
\begin_inset Formula $-$
\end_inset

 alleles in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 individuals, and a mild fitness cost for 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 alleles in A individuals; a constant value 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 (which will cancel out below) then controls the overall fitness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now consider applying this simple infection model to a single large populatio
n of host individuals, of whom we assume a fixed proportion 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{S}$
\end_inset

 carry the 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 allele and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{A}=1-f_{S}$
\end_inset

 do not.
 For a basic model, we assume discrete rounds of infection.
 On each generation, each individual is bitten by an infection mosquito
 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

, and if so, the mosquito behaves by sampling a parasite at random from
 the previous generation.
 If we let 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{+}^{(i)}$
\end_inset

 denote the frequency of 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 alleles among successful infections from the previous generation, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{-}^{(i)}=1-f_{+}^{(i)}$
\end_inset

, this leads to the following evolution equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{+}^{(i+1)}=\frac{f_{A}f_{+}^{(i)}\gamma_{+A}+f_{S}f_{+}^{(i)}\gamma_{+S}}{f_{A}f_{+}^{(i)}\gamma_{+A}+f_{S}f_{+}^{(i)}\gamma_{+S}+f_{A}f_{-}^{(i)}\gamma_{-A}+f_{S}f_{-}^{(i)}\gamma_{-S}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation can be explained as follows.
 We suppose there are 
\begin_inset Formula $N>>0$
\end_inset

 individuals in the host population, and consider the number of these at
 generation 
\begin_inset Formula $i+1$
\end_inset

 who
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
carry a given host allele 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 either 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{A}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{S}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
are bitten by an infected mosquito at iteration 
\begin_inset Formula $i+1$
\end_inset

 (this happens with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
the mosquito carries the given parasite allele 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

(i.e.
 either 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{+}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{-}$
\end_inset

);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
and the infection is successful (which happens with probabiltiy 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{xy}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This leads to a computation that in total there are 
\begin_inset Formula $Nf_{y}\cdot\eta f_{x}\cdot\gamma_{xy}$
\end_inset

 successful infections with the given host and parasite alleles at timepoint
 
\begin_inset Formula $i+1$
\end_inset

.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:evolution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is then obtained from this by dividing the total number of individuals
 infected with 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 alleles by the total number of infected individuals; the values 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 all cancel from this equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: independent pops"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

a shows the evolution of this equation using the fitness values from the
 right side of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:evolution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, in ten populations with S allele frequencies from 0 to 0.15.
 It is clear that, despite the opposing fitness effects encoded in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 allele either ultimately fixes or is lost from the population, i.e.
 essentially either 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $-$
\end_inset

 undergoes a selective sweep.
 In fact, this behaviour can be established directly for the above model
 (regardless of the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

) by searching for fixed points of the Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:evolution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Analysis of this equation shows that the fixed points occur at 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{+}=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{+}=1$
\end_inset

, except that the frequencies will remain constant if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f_{S}}{f_{A}}=-\frac{\gamma_{+A}-\gamma_{-A}}{\gamma_{+S}-\gamma_{-S}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For given fitnesses 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{S}$
\end_inset

 is above this threshold value then the 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 allele will sweep to fixation; otherwise the 
\begin_inset Formula $-$
\end_inset

 allele will; for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 values shown in Figure 3 this is 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{S}=10\%$
\end_inset

.
 This equilibrium state is clearly unlikely to apply in real populations
 where stochastic variation in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 frequency is also present.
\end_layout

