\begin_layout Section*
Aside: The effects of host evolution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
NOTE: not sure whether appropriate to include this section, which is also
 INCOMPLETE.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above discussion assumes for simplicity that the host allele does not
 change frequency.
 Standard models for host-pathogen co-evolution do allow for evolution of
 host frequencies and a typical outcome is 'red queen' dynamics, in which
 host and pathogen allele frequencies oscillate around equilbrium values
 due to the time-dependent negative feedback
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ebert:2020aa"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, there are two complications in the above.
 The first is that for sickle haemoglobin there is a clear external force
 - sickle cell disease - which limits the frequency that HbS allele can
 attain.
 The second is that parasites evolve over much shorter timescales than humans
 (with e.g.
 at least tens of full parasite 'generations' including transmission, per
 human generation).
 Nevertheless, if the behavour in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: independent pops"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

b is apparent, a possibility is that parasites reach stable equilbrium which
 then evolve slowly over time with the evolution of HbS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To explore this we extended the above model to include S allele evolution.
 As above we assume that a proportion 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 of individuals are bitten by an infected mosquito in each generation, and
 we assume that a proportion 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\leq1$
\end_inset

 of individual with successful infections survive the infection.
 To model the effect of death due to sickle disease, we further assume that
 a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\cdot f_{S}^{2}$
\end_inset

 of the remaining survivors with genotype 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is also lost.
 The number of surviving hosts with 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 alleles after iteration 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 can now be computed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N_{S}^{(i+1)}=\left(1-\kappa\cdot f_{S}^{2}\right)\cdot\left[Nf_{s}(1-\eta)+Nf_{S}\eta\cdot\left(f_{+}\gamma_{+S}+f_{-}\gamma_{-S}\right)\cdot\alpha\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The number of surviving hosts with 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 alleles can similarly be computed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N_{A}^{(i+1)}=\left[Nf_{A}(1-\eta)+Nf_{A}\eta\cdot\left(f_{+}\gamma_{+A}+f_{-}\gamma_{-A}\right)\cdot\alpha\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{S}^{(i+1)}=\frac{N_{S}^{(i+1)}}{N_{A}^{(i+1)}+N_{S}^{(i+1)}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

determine the rate of this host evolution.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

 (no death due to malaria) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa=0$
\end_inset

 then no host evolution occurs and the model reduces to the model studied
 above.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha<1$
\end_inset

 then deaths due to malaria affect frequencies, and if 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa>0$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{S}$
\end_inset

 is further affected by deaths due to homozygotes.
 This simple model clearly does not capture detailed aspects of the sickle
 haemoglobin / malaria relationship, but does reflect the basic effects
 on mortality of malaria infection and of sickle cell disease.
\end_layout

